{"parse":{"title":"kid","pageid":39973,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|Appendix:Variations of \"kid\"}}\n==Translingual==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{abbrev|mul|en:'''K'''osh'''i'''n}} with {{m|mul|d}} as a placeholder.\n\n===Symbol===\n{{mul-symbol}}\n\n# {{ISO 639|3}}\n\n===See also===\n* {{langcat}}\n\n==English==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈkɪd/|[ˈkʰɪd]}}\n** {{audio|en|en-us-kid.ogg|a=US}}\n* {{rhymes|en|ɪd|s=1}}\n* {{hyph|en|kid}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n[[Image:Goat kid444.jpg|thumb|right|A goat kid.]]\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|kide}}, from {{der|en|non|kið||young goat}}, from {{der|en|gem-pro|*kidją}}, {{m|gem-pro|*kittīną||goatling, kid}}, perhaps from {{der|en|ine-pro|*gʰaydn-}}, {{m|ine-pro|*ǵʰaydn-||goat}} or {{der|en|ine-pro|*gidʰ-||kid, goatling, little goat}}. Compare {{cog|sv|-}} and {{cog|da|kid}}, {{cog|de|Kitz}} and {{m|de|Kitze}}, {{cog|sq|kedh}} and {{m|sq|kec}}. The sense of {{m|en|child}} has been in use since the 1590s as [[slang]], and since the 1840s in informal use.<ref>{{R:Online Etymology Dictionary}}</ref><ref>{{R:Grose Vulgar Tongue|page=124|passage='''{{smallcaps|Kid}}''', a child.|nodot=1}}</ref>\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun|~}}\n\n# {{lb|en|informal}} A [[child]], [[adolescent]]{{,}} or {{lb|en|loosely}} a [[young adult]]. \n#: {{syn|en|Thesaurus:child}}\n#: {{ux|en|She's a '''kid'''. It's normal for her to have imaginary friends.}}\n#* {{RQ:Dickens Oliver Twist|volume=II|page=12|passage=“So you’ve got the '''kid''',” said Sikes, when they had all reached the room: closing the door as he spoke. ¶ “Yes, here he is,” replied Nancy. ¶ “Did he come quiet?” inquired Sikes. ¶ “Like a lamb,” rejoined Nancy.}}\n#* {{RQ:Marsh Beetle|chapter=What the Tidings Were|page=269|passage=I said, “I’ll send the first sane soul I meet to keep you company.” As luck would have it, I never met one,—only '''kids''', and a baker, who wouldn’t leave his cart, or take it with him either.}}\n#* {{RQ:C. S. Lewis Magician's Nephew|passage=\"I should never dream of calling a '''kid''' like you a woman,\" said Digory loftily.}}\n#* {{RQ:Allingham China Governess|The Beanspiller|186|‘No,’ said Luke, grinning at her. ‘You’re not dull enough! {{...}} What about the '''kid'''’s clothes? I don’t suppose they were anything to write home about, but didn’t you keep anything? A bootee or a bit of embroidery or anything at all?’}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|date=July 5 2007|author=w:Barack Obama|title=s:Remarks of Senator Barack Obama to the National Education Association Annual Meeting\n|passage=Our '''kids''' are why all of you are in this room today. Our '''kids''' are why you wake up wondering how you'll make a difference and go to bed thinking about tomorrow's lesson plan. Our '''kids''' are why you walk into that classroom every day even when you're not getting the support, or the pay, or the respect that you deserve - because you believe that every child should have a chance to succeed; that every child can be taught.}}\n#* {{quote-song|en|artist={{w|Drake (musician)|Drake}}|title=March 14|album=Scorpion|year=2018|passage=She not my lover like \"Billie Jean\", but the '''kid''' is mine}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|year=2019|month=October|author=Ian Walmsley|title=Cleaning up|journal=Modern Railways|page=44|text=Network Rail is now the biggest '''kid''' in the playground, so if it doesn't want to play it doesn't have to, and the trees still fall down every time someone gives a low pressure system a name.}}\n## {{lb|en|informal}} A person whose [[childhood]] took place in a particular time period or area.\n##: {{ux|en|Only '90s '''kids''' will remember this toy.}}\n##: {{ux|en|He's been living in Los Angeles for years now, but he's a Florida '''kid'''.}}\n## {{lb|en|informal}} One's son or daughter, regardless of age.\n##: {{ux|en|This is Bobby, he is our youngest '''kid'''.}}\n## {{lb|en|in the vocative}} {{ng|Used as a form of address for a child, teenager or young adult.}}\n##* {{quote-av|en|year=1942|author=w:Julius J. Epstein; w:Philip G. Epstein; {{w|Howard Koch (screenwriter)|Howard Koch}}|title={{w|Casablanca (film)|Casablanca}}|role=Rick|actor=Humphrey Bogart|passage=Here's looking at you, '''kid'''.}}\n## {{lb|en|colloquial}} An [[inexperienced]] person or one in a [[junior]] position.\n##* '''2007''' June 3, {{w|Eben Moglen}}, speech, ''Freeing the Mind: Free Software and the end of proprietary culture'',\n##*: I remember as a '''kid''' lawyer working at IBM in the summer of 1983, when a large insurance company in Hartford, Connecticut, for the first time asked to buy 12000 IBM PCs in a single order.\n# {{senseid|en|Q13048847}}A young [[goat]].\n#: {{ux|en|He treated the oxen like they didn't exist, but he treated the goat '''kid''' like a puppy.}}\n#* {{RQ:Defoe Crusoe|page=249|passage=I went indeed intending to kill a '''Kid''' out of my own Flock, and bring him home and dreſs it. But as I was going, I ſaw a She Goat lying down in the Shade, and two young '''Kids''' ſitting by her, {{...}}}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1769|author={{w|Firishta}}|tlr={{w|Alexander Dow}}|title=Tales translated from the Persian of Inatulla of Delhi|volume=I|publisher=P. and W. Wilson et al.|location=Dublin|page=iv|text=The lofty mountains roſe faint to the ſight and loſt their foreheads in the diſtant ſkies: the little hills, cloathed in darker green and ſkirted with embroidered vales, diſcovered the ſecret haunts of '''kids''' and bounding roes.}}\n## {{lb|en|uncountable}} [[kidskin|Kidskin]].\n##: {{syn|en|kid leather}}\n##* {{quote-text|en|year=1912|author=w:Jean Webster|title=[[s:Daddy-Long-Legs/Letter 3|Daddy-Long-Legs: Letter 3]]\n|passage=I have three pairs of '''kid''' gloves. I've had '''kid''' mittens before from the Christmas tree, but never real '''kid''' gloves with five fingers.}}\n## {{lb|en|uncountable}} The meat of a young goat.\n##: {{syn|en|cabrito|capretto}}\n##* {{RQ:Scott Ivanhoe|I|VII|pages=85–86|pageref=85|text=So saying, he gathered together, and brought to a flame, the decaying brands which lay scattered on the ample hearth; took from the larger board a mess of pottage and seethed '''kid''', placed it upon the small table at which he had himself supped, and without waiting the Jew's thanks, went to the other side of the hall;—{{nb...|nospace=1}}.}}\n# A young [[antelope]].\n# {{lb|en|dated}} A [[deception]]; an act of kidding somebody.\n# {{lb|en|nautical}} A small wooden [[mess]] [[tub]] in which [[sailor]]s received their food.\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1830|author=James Fenimore Cooper|title=The Water-witch, Or, The Skimmer of the Seas\n|passage=peaceable, well-disposed chaps as ever eat duff (dough) out of a '''kid'''}}\n#* {{RQ:Melville Omoo|chapter=Reception from the Frenchman|page=109|passage=We fasted till night, when one of the boys came along with a couple of \"'''kids'''\" containing a thin, saffron-coloured fluid, with oily particles floating on top. The young wag told us this was soup: it turned out to be nothing more than oleaginous warm water.}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col3|en|title=Terms derived from ''kid'' (noun)|handle with kid gloves|kidsy\n|kiddo|kiddy|kidlike|kidly|kidskin|logo kid|kidsy|kid stuff|kidult|quiz kid|rich kid|snowkid|whiz kid|adult third culture kid|ball kid|boomerang kid|candy kid|club kid|comeback kid|cool kid|divorced kid|Dongola kid|e-kid|kandi kid|kid brother|kid glove|kid on the square|kid show|kid sister|kid table|kid-dom|kid-glove|latchkey kid|like a kid in a candy store\n|new kid in town|new kid on the block|oor kid|our kid|preacher's kid syndrome| iPad kid|kid porn|like a kid at Christmas|like a kid on Christmas morning|quiz-kid|rich-kid|scene kid|struggle kid|theater kid|theatre kid|third culture kid|anarkid|biokid|band kid|cyberkid|emokid|everykid|fankid|furkid|godkid|grandkid|kidcom|kidcore|kidder|kiddie|kiddiot|kiddish|kiddom|kideo|kidfic|kidfluence|kidfluencer|kidfucker|kidhood|kidkind|kidless|kidlet|kidling|kidlit|Kidman|kidnap|kidology|kidpic|kidproof|kidsicle|kidsman|kidspeak|kidvid|merkid|schoolkid|stepkid|superkid|transkid|vidkid|wonderkid|whiz-kid|whizz kid|wor kid|in kid|no sabo kid|is that what the kids are calling it these days|Bebe's kid|street kid|treat like a Make-A-Wish kid|big kid}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|child (colloq.)}}\n* Arabic: {{t+|ar|طِفْل|m}}\n*: Moroccan Arabic: {{t|ary|دري|m|tr=darri}}, {{t|ary|بعلوك|m|tr=baʕlūk}}, {{t|ary|برهوش|m|tr=barhūš}}\n* Armenian: {{t+|hy|բալիկ}}, Armenian: {{t+|hy|երեխա}}\n* Baluchi: {{t|bal|چک|tr=cukk}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|хлапе|n}}, {{t+|bg|хлапак|m}}, {{t|bg|хлапачка|f}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|nen|m}}, {{t+|ca|nena|f}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Cantonese: {{t+|yue|細路|tr=sai3 lou4}}, {{t+|yue|細路仔|tr=sai3 lou4 zai2}}\n*: Hokkien: {{t+|nan-hbl|囡仔|tr=[[gín-á]]}}\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|孩子|tr=háizi}}, {{t+|cmn|小孩|tr=xiǎohái}}\n* Danish: {{t+|da|barn}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|kind|n}}\n* Esperanto: {{t+|eo|infano}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|kersa}}, {{t+|fi|skidi}}, {{t+|fi|pirpana}}, {{t+|fi|ipana}}, {{t+|fi|nassikka}}, {{t+|fi|penska}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|gamin|m}}, {{t+|fr|gosse|m}}, {{t+|fr|bambin|m}}, {{t+|fr|môme|m|f}}\n* Georgian: {{t|ka|ბავშვი}}\n* German: {{t+|de|Kind|n}}\n* Gothic: {{t|got|𐍆𐍂𐌰𐍃𐍄𐍃|m}}, {{t|got|𐌱𐌰𐍂𐌽|n}}\n* Greek:\n*: Ancient Greek: {{t|grc|παῖς|m|f}}, {{t|grc|παίδιον|n}}, {{t|grc|τέκνον|n}}\n* Guarani:\n*: Paraguayan Guarani: {{t-check|gug|mitã}}\n* Hebrew: {{t+|he|ילד}}\n* Hindi: {{t+|hi|बच्चा|m}}, {{t+|hi|बच्ची|f}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|kölyök}}, {{t+|hu|srác}}\n* Icelandic: {{t+|is|krakki|m}}\n* Ido: {{t+|io|puereto}}\n* Indonesian: {{t+|id|anak}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|bambino|m}}, {{t+|it|bimbo|m}}\n* Japanese: {{t+|ja|子供|tr=kodomo}}, {{t+|ja|子|tr=ko}}\n* Khmer: {{t|km|ក្មេងម្នាក់|tr=kmeɛŋ mneak}}\n* Kyrgyz: {{t+|ky|бала}}, {{t+|ky|наристе}}\n* Macedonian: {{t|mk|клинец|m}}, {{t|mk|клинка|f}}\n* Maltese: {{t|mt|tfajjel|m}}\n* Marshallese: {{t|mh|boea}}\n* Navajo: {{t|nv|chąąmąʼii}}\n* Norwegian: {{t+|no|barn|n}}, {{t+|no|unge|m}}\n* Persian: {{t+|fa|بچه|tr=bačče}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|dzieciak|n}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|criança|f}}, {{t+|pt|miúdo|m}} {{qualifier|Portugal}}, {{t+|pt|piá|m}} {{qualifier|Paraná}}, {{t+|pt|guri|m}} {{qualifier|Rio Grande do Sul}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|ребёнок|m}}, {{t+|ru|па́рень|m}}, {{t+|ru|девчо́нка|f}}\n* Sanskrit: {{t+|sa|शिशु|m}}, {{t+|sa|बालक|m}}, {{t+|sa|जात|m|n}}\n* Serbo-Croatian: {{t+|sh|klinac|m}}, {{t+|sh|klinka|f}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|niño|m}}, {{t|es|buqui|m}}, {{t+|es|chamaco|m}}, {{t+|es|chamo|m}}, {{t+|es|chango|m}}, {{t+|es|chino|m}}, {{t+|es|churumbel}}, {{t+|es|cipote|m}}, {{t+|es|crío|f}}, {{t+|es|güila|f}}, {{t+|es|huerco|m}}, {{t+|es|nene|m}}, {{t+|es|patojo|m}}, {{t+|es|chiquillo}}, {{t|es|zagal}}, {{t+|es|chaval}}, {{t|es|chibolo|m}}, {{t+|es|escuintle|m}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|unge|c}}\n* Tagalog: {{t+|tl|bata}}\n* Turkish: {{t+|tr|çocuk}}\n* Ukrainian: {{t+|uk|дити́на}}, {{t|uk|малю́к}}, {{t|uk|дитя́}}, {{t|uk|маля́}}\n* Vietnamese: {{t+|vi|nhóc}}, {{t+|vi|con nít}}\n* Volapük: {{qualifier|♂♀}} {{t+|vo|cil}}, {{qualifier|♂}} {{t+|vo|hicil}}, {{qualifier|♂}} {{t+|vo|jicil}}, {{qualifier|hypocoristic, ♂♀}} {{t|vo|cilül}}, {{qualifier|hypocoristic, ♂}} {{t|vo|hicilül}}, {{qualifier|hypocoristic, ♀}} {{t|vo|jicilül}}\n* Walloon: {{t+|wa|gamén|m}}, {{t+|wa|råpén|m}}, {{t+|wa|roufion|m}}, {{t+|wa|djambot|m}}\n* Zazaki: {{t+|zza|qeç}}, {{t+|zza|domon}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|young person (colloq.)}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|хлапе́|n}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|nen|m}}, {{t+|ca|nena|f}}\n* Danish: {{t+|da|unge}}, {{t|da|en ung|c}}\n* Esperanto: {{t|eo|junulo}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|kersa}}, {{t+|fi|skidi}}, {{t+|fi|nassikka}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|gamin|m}}, {{t+|fr|gosse|m}}, {{qualifier|Québec}} {{t+|fr|flo|m}}\n* German: {{t+|de|Bursche|m}}, {{t+|de|Bube|m}}, {{t+|de|Halbstarker|m}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|gyerek}}, {{t+|hu|srác}}, {{t+|hu|suhanc}}\n* Icelandic: {{t+|is|barn|n}}, {{t+|is|krakki|m}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|ragazzo|m}}\n* Japanese: {{t+|ja|童|tr=warawa}}\n* Korean: {{t+|ko|어린이}}\n* Marshallese: {{t|mh|boea}}\n* Norwegian: {{t+|no|ungdom|m}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|dzieciak|m}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|jovem|m|f}}, {{t+|pt|moleque}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|мальчи́шка|m}}, {{t+|ru|девчо́нка|f}}, {{t+|ru|паца́н|m}}\n* Serbo-Croatian: {{t+|sh|dečko|m}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|chico|m}}, {{t+|es|muchacho|m}}, {{t+|es|cabro|m}}, {{t+|es|chango|m}}, {{t+|es|chaval|m}}, {{t+|es|chavalo|m}}, {{t+|es|chavo|m}}, {{t|es|chibolo|m}}, {{t+|es|chiquillo|m}}, {{t+|es|lolo|m}}, {{t+|es|pelado|m}}, {{t+|es|pibe|m|f}}, {{t+|es|chamaco|m}}, {{t+|es|péndex|m|f}}\n* Turkish: {{t+|tr|delikanlı}}\n* Ukrainian: {{t|uk|хлопчи́на}}, {{t+|uk|ді́вчина}}\n* Zazaki: {{t|zza|tut}}, {{t|zza|pıt}}, {{t+|zza|resaye|c}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|young goat}}\n* Arabic: {{t|ar|جَدْي|m}}\n*: Egyptian Arabic: {{t|arz|جدي|m|tr=gedi}}\n* Armenian: {{t+|hy|ուլ}}\n* Aromanian: {{t|rup|ed}}\n* Asturian: {{t+|ast|cabritu|m}}\n* Belarusian: {{t|be|казляня́|n}}\n* Breton: {{t|br|gaorig}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t|bg|я́ре|n}}, {{t|bg|козле|n}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|cabrit|m}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{t|cmn|小山羊|tr=xiǎoshānyáng}}\n* Cornish: {{t|kw|minen}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|kůzle|n}}\n* Danish: {{t+|da|gedekid}}, {{t+|da|kid|n}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|geitje|n}}\n* Esperanto: {{t|eo|kaprido}}\n* Faroese: {{t|fo|geitarlamb|n}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|kili}}, {{t+|fi|vohla}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|chevreau|m}}, {{t+|fr|biquet|m}}\n* Galician: {{t|gl|curcio|m}}, {{t+|gl|chibo|m}}, {{t+|gl|cabuxo|m}}, {{t|gl|bodeixo|m}}, {{t+|gl|rexelo|m}}, {{t+|gl|cabrito|m}}, {{t+|gl|añagoto|m}}\n* Georgian: {{t|ka|თიკანი}}\n* German: {{t+|de|Kitz|n}}, {{t+|de|Zicklein|n}}, {{t|de|Geißlein|n}}, {{t|de|Gitzi|n}} {{qualifier|Switzerland}}\n*: Middle High German: {{t|gmh|zickelīn|n}}\n*: Old High German: {{t|goh|zickī|n}}, {{t|goh|zickīn|n}}, {{t|goh|kizzī|n}}, {{t|goh|kizzīn|n}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|κατσικάκι|n}}, {{t+|el|κατσίκι|n}}\n*: Ancient Greek: {{t|grc|ἔριφος|m|f}}\n* Greenlandic: {{t|kl|savaasaaraq}}\n* Hebrew: {{t+|he|גדי|tr=g'dí|m}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|gida}}, {{t+|hu|gödölye}}\n* Icelandic: {{t+|is|kið|n}}\n* Indonesian: {{t|id|anak kambing}}\n* Interlingua: {{t|ia|capretto}}\n* Irish: {{t|ga|meannán|m}}\n*: Middle Irish: {{t|mga|menn|m}}, {{t|mga|mendán|m}}\n*: Old Irish: {{t|sga|mend|m}}\n* Italian: {{t|it|capretto|m}}\n* Japanese: {{t|ja|仔ヤギ|tr=ko-yagi}}\n* Kashmiri: {{t|ks|مۄنٛگُر|m}}, {{t|ks|مۄنٛگٕر|f}}\n* Kazakh: {{t|kk|лақ}}\n* Kurdish:\n*: Northern Kurdish: {{t+|kmr|karik|m|f}}, {{t+|kmr|kar|m|f}}\n* Kyrgyz: {{t+|ky|улак|m}}\n* Latin: {{t|la|haedus|m}}\n* Latvian: {{t|lv|kazlēns}}\n* Lithuanian: {{t|lt|oželis}}, {{t|lt|ožkutis}}\n* Macedonian: {{t|mk|јаре|n}}\n* Maltese: {{t|mt|gidi|m}}, {{t|mt|gidja|f}}\n* Manx: {{t|gv|mannan}}\n* Navajo: {{t|nv|tłʼízí yázhí}}\n* Norman: {{t|nrf|p'tit bichot|m}}, {{t|nrf|bichette|f}}\n* Norwegian: {{t|no|killing|m}}, {{t+|no|kje|n}}\n* Occitan: {{t+|oc|cabrit|m}}\n* Old Church Slavonic: {{t|cu|козьлѧ|n}}\n* Old Norse: {{t|non|kið|n}}\n* Persian: {{t+|fa|بزغاله|tr=bozġâle}}, {{t|fa|هیرک|tr=hirak}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|koźlę|n}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|cabrita|f}}, {{t+|pt|cabrito|m}}\n* Punjabi: {{t+|pa|ਮੇਮਣਾ}}\n* Romanian: {{t+|ro|ied|m}}, {{t+|ro|iadă|f}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|козлёнок|m}}\n* Scottish Gaelic: {{t|gd|meann|m}}\n* Serbo-Croatian:\n*: Cyrillic: {{t|sh|јаре|n}}, {{t|sh|козлић|m}}\n*: Latin: {{t+|sh|jare|n}}, {{t|sh|kozlić|m}}\n* Sicilian: {{t+|scn|ciareddu|m}}\n* Slovak: {{t|sk|kozľa|n}}, {{t|sk|kozliatko|n}}\n* Slovene: {{t|sl|kozliček|m}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|cabrito|m}}, {{t+|es|chivo|m}}\n* Swahili: {{t+|sw|mwanambuzi}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|killing|c}}, {{t+|sv|kid|n}}\n* Tagalog: {{t|tl|batang kambing}}\n* Telugu: {{t+|te|మేకపిల్ల}}\n* Turkish: {{t+|tr|oğlak}}\n*: Ottoman Turkish: {{t|ota|اوغلاق|tr=oğlak}}\n* Turkmen: {{t|tk|guzy}}\n* Tuvan: {{t|tyv|анай}}\n* Ukrainian: {{t+|uk|козеня́|n}}, {{t+|uk|цапеня́|n}}\n* Uyghur: {{t|ug|ئوغلاق}}\n* Volapük: {{qualifier|♂♀}} {{t+|vo|kaparül}}, {{qualifier|♂}} {{t|vo|hikaparül}}, {{qualifier|♀}} {{t|vo|jikaparül}}\n* Welsh: {{t|cy|myn|m}}\n* Wolof: {{t|wo|tef|alt=tef bi}}\n* Yiddish: {{t|yi|ציגעלע|n}}\n* Zazaki: {{t|zza|kavrek}}, {{t+|zza|bızêk|c}}, {{t|zza|gıdık|c}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-see|kidskin}}\n\n{{trans-top|young antelope}}\n* Zazaki: {{t|zza|kehari}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n====Verb====\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|transitive|colloquial|usually present participle}} To [[dupe]] or [[deceive]].\n#: {{coi|en|Are you '''kidding''' me?}}\n#: {{coi|en|I '''kid''' you not!}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1965|author=James Holledge\n|title=What Makes a Call Girl?|publisher=Horwitz Publications|location=London|page=76\n|passage=\"They are all very suspicious about the wording. I am always thinking up new ways of '''kidding''' them.\"}}\n## {{lb|en|transitive|colloquial|usually present participle}} To deceive or dupe as a joke.\n##: {{uxi|en|Stop '''kidding''' me! It's not funny.}}\n## {{lb|en|reflexive|usually present participle}} To deceive oneself by having unrealistic expectations.\n##: {{uxi|en|You're '''kidding''' yourself if you think you can be a rockstar.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive|colloquial|usually present participle}} To mock or make a fool of (someone) in a [[playful]] way.\n#: {{uxi|en|They were always '''kidding''' her for her stutter.}}\n# {{lb|en|intransitive|colloquial|usually present participle}} To [[joke]].\n#: {{coi|en|You must be '''kidding'''!}}\n#: {{coi|en|I'm only '''kidding'''!}}\n#: {{coi|en|No '''kidding'''!}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1914|author=Ernest Bramah|title=Max Carrados\n|passage=\"Blind!\" exclaimed the old fellow, sitting up in startled wonderment. \"You mean it, sir? You walk all right and you look at me as if you saw me. You're '''kidding''' surely.\"}}\n# {{lb|en|intransitive}} Of a goat: to [[give birth]].\n#: {{uxi|en|That nanny over there with the white tail has '''kidded''' every year for the last five years.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2008|author=w:Monte Dwyer|title=Red In The Centre: The Australian Bush Through Urban Eyes|publisher=Monyer Pty Ltd|page=200|text=\"They can '''kid''' twice a year if things are right, and they often throw twins and triplets.\"}}\n\n=====Usage notes=====\n* Generally rare outside of set phrases.\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col2|en|I kid you not| you're kidding|kid around|all kidding aside|kidding aside|who am I kidding|you've got to be kidding me}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|deceive (as a joke)}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t-check|bg|шегувам се}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|beetnemen}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|huiputtaa}}, {{t+|fi|narrata}}, {{t+|fi|petkuttaa}}, {{t+|fi|puijata}}, {{t|fi|laskea leikkiä}}\n* French: {{t-needed|fr}}\n*: Old French: {{t|fro|gaber}}\n* Galician: {{t-check|gl|zombar}}, {{t-check|gl|monearse}}\n* Georgian: {{t-check|ka|ღადავი}}\n* German: {{t+|de|an der Nase herumführen}}, {{t+|de|veräppeln}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|megviccel}}, {{t+|hu|hülyít}}, {{t+|hu|szívat}}, {{t+|hu|átráz}}\n* Icelandic: {{t|is|fíflast í}}\n* Irish: {{t|ga|dallamullóg a chur ar}}\n* Kyrgyz: {{t+check|ky|тамашалоо}}, {{t-check|ky|kалжың кылуу}}\n* Norwegian: {{t+check|no|tulle}}\n* Portuguese: {{t-needed|pt}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|надува́ть}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|narra}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|mock playfully}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|будалкам}}, {{t+|bg|занасям|impf}}, {{t|bg|занеса|pf}}, {{t|bg|майтапя се}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|plagen}}\n* Finnish: {{t|fi|tehdä pilaa}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|moquer|alt=se moquer}}, {{qualifier|Quebec}} {{t+|fr|niaiser}}, {{t+|fr|faire marcher}}, {{t+|fr|charrier}}\n*: Old French: {{t|fro|gaber}}\n* Galician: {{t-check|gl|mocarse}}, {{t-check|gl|leirear}}\n* German: {{t+|de|verarschen}}, {{t+|de|veräppeln}}\n* Hindi: {{t-check|hi|tr=ollu|sc=Deva}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|viccel}}\n* Icelandic: {{t|is|gera grín að}}\n* Irish: {{t|ga|bheith ag magadh faoi}}\n* Norwegian: {{t+check|no|lure}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|enganar}}, {{t+|pt|caçoar}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|дразни́ть}}, {{t-check|ru|подшу́чивать над}} {{qualifier|+ [[instrumental case|instrumental]]}}\n* Scottish Gaelic: {{t|gd|tarraing à}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|tomar el pelo}}\n* Swedish: {{t|sv|driva med}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|to joke}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t|bg|шегувам се}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|gekscheren}}\n* Esperanto: {{t|eo|blagi}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|vitsailla}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|blaguer}}, {{t+|fr|plaisanter}}, {{t+|fr|rigoler}}\n* Galician: {{t|gl|bulrarse}}, {{t|gl|chifrarse}}\n* Georgian: {{t|ka|ღადავი}}\n* German: {{t+|de|spaßen}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|viccel}}\n* Icelandic: {{t|is|gera grín}}\n* Irish: {{t|ga|bheith ag magadh}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|scherzare}}\n* Norwegian: {{t+|no|tulle}}, {{t|no|tøyse}}, {{t|no|kødde}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|brincar}}, {{t+|pt|zoar}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|шути́ть}}\n* Serbo-Croatian:\n*: Cyrillic: {{t|sh|ша̏лити|impf}}\n*: Latin: {{t+|sh|šȁliti|impf}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|skämta}}, {{t+|sv|skoja}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n====See also====\n{{col|en|suede|kid on}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nOf {{unc|en|title=uncertain}} origin. Possibly from {{inh|en|enm|*kidde}}, from {{inh|en|ang|*cydde|t=pouch, belly}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*kuddijā}}, derived from or related to {{der|en|gem-pro|*kuddô|t=bag, sack, pod, shell, husk}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{lb|en|UK|dialectal}} A [[seed pod]], usually of a [[leguminous]] plant.\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col|en|kidney<gloss:possibly>}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\nCompare {{cog|cy|cidysen}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{syn of|en|faggot||bundle of heath and furze}}.\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1631|author=w:Gervase Markham|title=Countrey Contentments|edition=4th|page=99|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=GAhlAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA99|passage=Now, for as much as this Fowle is a great deſtruction vnto the young Spawne or Frie of Fiſh, it ſhall bee good for the preſeruation thereof, to ſtake down into the bottomes of your Ponds good long '''Kids''' or Faggots of bruſh-woods, {{...}}}}\n\n===References===\n<references/>\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{pedia}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|en|a=dik|IDK|idk}}\n\n{{cln|en|terms of address}}\n{{C|en|Antelopes|Baby animals|Children|Comedy|Family members|Goats|Hides|Meats|People|Deception|Human behaviour}}\n\n==Danish==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|da|gmq-oda|kith}}, from {{inh|da|non|kið||young goat}}, from {{inh|da|gem-pro|*kidją}}, {{m|gem-pro|*kittīną||goatling, kid}}, perhaps from {{der|da|ine-pro|*gʰaydn-}}, {{m|ine-pro|*ǵʰaydn-||goat}} or {{der|da|ine-pro|*gidʰ-||kid, goatling, little goat}}. Compare {{cog|sv|-}} and {{cog|nb|kid}}, {{cog|en|kid}}, {{cog|de|Kitz}} and {{m|de|Kitze}}, {{cog|sq|kedh}} and {{m|sq|kec}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{da-noun|dc=1|et}}\n\n# A young [[goat]].\n\n====Declension====\n{{da-decl|dc=1|et}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|da|gedekid}}\n* {{l|da|råkid}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:DDO}}\n* {{R:ODS}}\n\n==French==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{ety|fr|:bor|en:kid}}\n{{bor+|fr|en|kid}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{fr-IPA|kide}}\n* {{audio|fr|LL-Q150 (fra)-0x010C-kid.wav}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{fr-noun|m}}\n\n# {{lb|fr|colloquial}} {{l|en|kid|t=child}}\n#: {{syn|fr|gamin|gosse|minot|q3=regional}}\n\n==Hungarian==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{affix|hu|ki|-d|t1=who|t2=your, of yours|pos2=possessive suffix|nocat=y}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{hu-IPA}}\n* {{hyphenation|hu|kid}}\n\n===Pronoun===\n{{head|hu|pronoun form}}\n\n# {{inflection of|hu|ki||2|s|spos|poss}}\n\n====Declension====\n{{hu-infl-nom|kide|e|n=sg}}\n\n{{cln|hu|3-letter words}}\n\n==Norwegian Bokmål==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{der|nb|da|kid}}. {{doublet|nb|kje|t1=goatling}} from {{cog|no|-}} {{m|nn|kje}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|nb|/çidː/}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{nb-noun-n1|kid|kid|kid}}\n\n# the [[meat]] of a [[goatling]]\n\n===References===\n* {{R:nb:OB}}\n\n{{cln|nb|terms inherited from Danish}}\n\n==Norwegian Nynorsk==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|head=kìd|nn|noun|g=n|definite singular|kidet|f1alt=kìdet|indefinite plural|kid|f2alt=kìd|definite plural|kidi|f3alt=kìdi}}\n\n# {{nn-former|kje|1917}}\n\n==Sikaritai==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|tty|noun}}\n\n# [[banana]]\n\n===Further reading===\n* Heljä & Duane Clouse, ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20200714080904/https://www.langlxmelanesia.com/LLM%20vol%2024%20no%201%20kirikiri%20and%20the%20western%20lakes%20plains%20languages%20(1).pdf Kirikiri and the Western Lakes Plains Languages]'' (1993)\n\n==Sumerian==\n\n===Romanization===\n{{sux-rom}}\n\n# {{romanization of|sux|𒆤|tr=kid}}\n\n==Swedish==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|sv|gmq-osw|kiþ}}, from {{inh|sv|non|kið}}, from {{inh|sv|gem-pro|*kidją}}‚ from {{der|sv|ine-pro|*gidʰ-}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{rhymes|sv|iːd|s=1}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{sv-noun|n}}\n\n# [[fawn]] {{gl|a young deer}}\n\n====Declension====\n{{sv-infl-noun-n-zero}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|sv|killing}}\n* {{l|sv|rådjurskid}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:svenska.se}}\n* {{R:runeberg.org|svetym|0397.html kid}}\n\n{{C|sv|Baby animals}}\n\n==Volapük==\n\n===Noun===\n{{vo-noun}}\n\n# [[kiss]]\n\n====Declension====\n{{vo-decl-noun}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:vo:Vödabuk}}"}}